{"parse":{"title":"League of the Physically Handicapped","pageid":52962240,"revid":858221151,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><p><b>The League of the Physically Handicapped</b> in New York City was formed in May 1935 to protest discrimination by the <a href=\"/wiki/Works_Progress_Administration\" title=\"Works Progress Administration\">Works Progress Administration</a> (WPA).<sup id=\"cite_ref-longmore_1-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-longmore-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup> The <a href=\"/wiki/Home_Relief\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Home Relief\">Home Relief Bureau</a> of <a href=\"/wiki/New_York_City\" title=\"New York City\">New York City</a> stamped applications by handicapped applicants with \"PH\" which stood for \"<a href=\"/wiki/Physical_disability\" title=\"Physical disability\">physically handicapped</a>\". Marked as \"unemployable\" disabled people were denied access to WPA-created jobs.<sup id=\"cite_ref-isr_2-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-isr-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\nMembers of the League held a sit-in at the Home Relief Bureau for nine days and a weekend sit-in at the WPA headquarters in June 1935.<sup id=\"cite_ref-nyt_3-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-nyt-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> These actions eventually led to the creation of 1,500 jobs for disabled workers in New York City in 1936.<sup id=\"cite_ref-zames_4-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-zames-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-timeline_5-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-timeline-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup><sup id=\"cite_ref-consumer_6-0\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-consumer-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> The league had dissolved by 1938.<sup id=\"cite_ref-isr_2-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-isr-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup>\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=League_of_the_Physically_Handicapped&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-longmore-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-longmore_1-0\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation journal\">Longmore, PK; Goldberger, David (December 2000). \"The League of the Physically Handicapped and the Great Depression: A Case Study in the New Disability History\". <i>The Journal of American History</i>. <b>87</b> (3): 888\u2013922. <a href=\"/wiki/Digital_object_identifier\" title=\"Digital object identifier\">doi</a>:<a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"//doi.org/10.2307/2675276\">10.2307/2675276</a>.</cite><span title=\"ctx_ver=Z39.88-2004&amp;rft_val_fmt=info%3Aofi%2Ffmt%3Akev%3Amtx%3Ajournal&amp;rft.genre=article&amp;rft.jtitle=The+Journal+of+American+History&amp;rft.atitle=The+League+of+the+Physically+Handicapped+and+the+Great+Depression%3A+A+Case+Study+in+the+New+Disability+History&amp;rft.volume=87&amp;rft.issue=3&amp;rft.pages=888-922&amp;rft.date=2000-12&amp;rft_id=info%3Adoi%2F10.2307%2F2675276&amp;rft.aulast=Longmore&amp;rft.aufirst=PK&amp;rft.au=Goldberger%2C+David&amp;rfr_id=info%3Asid%2Fen.wikipedia.org%3ALeague+of+the+Physically+Handicapped\" class=\"Z3988\"><span style=\"display:none;\">&#160;</span></span></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-isr-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\">^ <a href=\"#cite_ref-isr_2-0\"><sup><i><b>a</b></i></sup></a> <a href=\"#cite_ref-isr_2-1\"><sup><i><b>b</b></i></sup></a></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><cite class=\"citation web\">Rosenthal, Keith. <a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external text\" href=\"https://isreview.org/issue/90/pioneers-fight-disability-rights\">\"Pioneers in the fight for disability rights The League